You are tasked with building a chess game assistant that can solve the classic N-Queens problem: placing n queens on an n x n chessboard such that no two queens threaten each other. This means:

No two queens can share the same row.
No two queens can share the same column.
No two queens can share the same diagonal.
Input Format

A single integer n â€” the size of the chessboard and the number of queens.

Constraints

NA

Output Format

Print each solution as a block of n strings, each of length n.
Separate different solutions by a blank line.
The order of solutions does not matter.
Sample Input 0

4
Sample Output 0

.Q..
...Q
Q...
..Q.

..Q.
Q...
...Q
.Q..
Explanation 0

There are two distinct ways to place 4 queens on a 4x4 board without conflict. Each solution block shows one valid board arrangement.

Sample Input 1

1
Sample Output 1

Q
Explanation 1

A 1x1 board only has one cell, so the single queen goes there.

